      <td bgcolor="#D40000"><div align="center" class="style14 style22">
       <div align="left" class="style2">The Bail Process in Connecticut </div>
      </div></td>
     </tr>
    </table>
    <blockquote>
     <p><span class="style7">How&nbsp;Bail&nbsp;Works in Connecticut:<br />
      </span>     When a person is arrested in Connecticut, they are taken to either
      a state or municiple law enforcement station to be booked and processed.
      After processing, a person has options for release. Bail is set to
      ensure the appearance of the defendant in court until their case has been
      disposed.</p>
     <p><span class="style7"><img src="images/cuffs.jpg" alt="ct bail bonds" width="240" height="163" align="right" />Who Sets Bail in Connecticut:</span><br />
      A Police Officer, Bail Commissioner or Judge sets bonds accordingly.&nbsp; The
      amount of bail set is usually based on the severity of the alleged&nbsp;crime,
      the defendants previous criminal record and the defendants ties (or lack
      of ties) to the community.</p>
     <p><span class="style7">How We Help:<br />
      </span> Upon your phone call to&nbsp;Statewide Bail Bonds, we will take the
      information you give on the defendant and immediately let you know what
      it will take to get your loved one released from jail. The state of connecticut
      insurance department requires that the premium on any given bond to be
      10% up to 5,000 dollars and 7% over 5,000 dollars. Cash, check or credit
      card is acceptable. We will also be happy to work out a reasonable payment
      plan, based on your particular financial needs.</p>
     <p><span class="style7">Our Role:</span><br />
      Statewide Bail Bonds guarantees full amount of the bond to the court. We guarantee
      the defendant's appearance at court for each and every existing court date.
      Collateral on bonds are not always required but high bonds do require some
      form of collateral.</p>
     <p><span class="style7">Collateral can consist of:</span></p>
     <ul>
      <li>	 Homes</li>
      <li>Cars&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
      <li> Cash</li>
     </ul>
     <p class="style21">When the case is finalized and the defendant has NOT missed a court date,
      collateral is always returned.</p>
    </blockquote>
